# Git Workflow

## Protected branches

`master` and `develop` must not receive **direct feature work** (no committing fixes/features on the branch tip and pushing). Changes land only through the flows below.

## Branch naming

| Purpose | Pattern | Merges into |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| Feature | `feature/YAIT-N-short-description` | `develop` (PR) |
| Bugfix / chore tied to an issue | `fix/YAIT-N-short-description` | `develop` (PR) |
| Release prep | `release/vX.Y.Z` | `master` (PR or reviewed merge; see below) |
| Production emergency | `hotfix/YAIT-N-short-description` | `master` then backport to `develop` (PRs) |

If there is **no** tracker issue (rare), use `chore/no-issue-<slug>` and put `Refs: none` in the commit body (hook allows it).

## Canonical path: day-to-day code

1. Branch from up-to-date `develop`: `git fetch origin && git checkout develop && git pull && git checkout -b fix/YAIT-N-slug` (or `feature/…`).
2. Implement; **`make audit` must pass** before push.
3. Push branch; open **PR → `develop`**; merge via GitHub (merge or squash per policy below).
4. Delete the remote branch after merge.

**Rebase** the topic branch on `origin/develop` before merge if it has drifted.

## Canonical path: release (version tag + changelog)

This is the **only** allowed way to move release artifacts onto `master`. It resolves the apparent conflict between “do not commit on `master`” and “releases live on `master`”: you never author commits **on** `master`; you merge a **release branch** that already contains the changelog commit.

1. `git fetch origin && git checkout develop && git pull origin develop`
2. `git checkout -b release/vX.Y.Z` (new branch from `develop`), or reset an existing local `release/vX.Y.Z` to `develop` if redoing.
3. Run **`make changelog`** on this branch. If output is wrong, **fix `cliff.toml` or tooling**—do not hand-edit `CHANGELOG.md` (see `.cursor/rules/semver-changelog.mdc`).
4. Commit on the release branch only: `chore(release): prepare vX.Y.Z` with body `Refs: none` (or the release-tracking issue if you use one).
5. Push `release/vX.Y.Z` and merge into **`master`** via **GitHub PR** (preferred) or an explicit local `git merge --no-ff` + push **only as the release merge**, not as everyday workflow.
6. On the resulting `master` tip: `git tag -a vX.Y.Z -m "release: vX.Y.Z"` and push the tag (triggers release CI when configured).
7. Merge **`master` back into `develop`** (PR or merge commit) so both lines stay aligned.

Deploy: **`make deploy VERSION=vX.Y.Z`** only after the tag exists on `master` per `deploy.mdc`.

## Canonical path: hotfix

1. Branch from **`master`**: `hotfix/YAIT-N-…`.
2. Fix; PR → **`master`**; tag new PATCH version; deploy if needed.
3. Backport: PR the same fix (or merge `master` into `develop`) so `develop` is not missing the fix.

## Conventional commits

Format: `<type>(<scope>): <description>`

**Types:** feat, fix, refactor, test, docs, chore, perf

**Scopes:** store, api, handler, mcp, auth, middleware, board, deps, ci

**Examples:**
- `feat(mcp): add delete_project tool`
- `fix(auth): prevent session fixation on login`
- `test(store): add table-driven tests for project CRUD`
- `chore(deps): bump modernc.org/sqlite to v1.49`

**Body:** `Refs: YAIT-N` or `Refs: none` (required by `.githooks/commit-msg` except merge/revert lines).

**Breaking changes:** add `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer

## Other rules

- One logical change per commit (atomic commits)
- Squash-merge only if the topic branch has noisy WIP commits
- Delete remote topic branches after merge
